    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Hmph, neutrophilia and lymphocytosis, you ask? It's all about the timing of the goblin horde's arrival, really. Think of it like this: when a nasty, sudden goblin infestation hits your system—an *acute* infection—you get a massive surge of neutrophils. These guys are the frontline shock troops, the quick-response goblin skirmishers.\n\nIn an acute setting, the body is throwing everything it has at the immediate threat, like a sudden swarm of particularly aggressive, mud-caked goblins. Neutrophils are the first ones to mobilize, rushing to the site of infection to gobble up the invaders. So, if you see neutrophilia acutely, it screams \"immediate, bacterial, messy goblin fight!\" It's fast, it's loud, and it's usually a brute-force response.\n\nNow, when we talk about *chronic* infections, things get more nuanced, like a slow, creeping infestation of particularly cunning, sneaky goblins who hide in the shadows. This is where lymphocytosis steps in. Lymphocytes—the T-cells and B-cells—are the strategists and the long-term siege engineers. They take time to multiply, to learn",
      "source": "target",
