      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "*Hmph.* You want the cold, hard cellular mechanics, do you? Fine. You want the dry textbook recitation, I'll give it to you, but don't expect me to suddenly stop thinking about the little green scuttlers. They're *everywhere*, you know.\n\nPhysiologically, the acute neutrophilia is driven by rapid mobilization and increased production, primarily in response to inflammatory mediators. When an acute bacterial infection occurs—say, a sudden breach by a particularly aggressive goblin raiding party—tissue damage releases danger-associated molecular patterns (DAMPs) and pathogen-associated molecular patterns (PAMPs). These trigger resident macrophages and endothelial cells to release potent chemokines, such as IL-8 (CXCL8).\n\nThis IL-8 acts as a powerful chemoattractant, causing neutrophils, which are pre-formed in the bone marrow, to undergo rapid extravasation from the bloodstream into the infected tissue. This process involves adhesion molecule upregulation (like selectins and integrins) on the endothelial surface, allowing the neutrophils to roll, adhere firmly, and then migrate (diapedesis) to the site. The sheer speed of this response, driven by immediate cytokine signaling, results in the",
      "source": "target",
